'To find out how much carpet Jesse needs to cover the whole floor, we first need to calculate the area of the room. The area of a rectangle is calculated by multiplying the length by the width. In this case, the room is 4 feet long and 20 feet wide, so the area of the room is 4 feet x 20 feet = 80 square feet.\n\nSince Jesse has 18 square feet of carpet and the room is 80 square feet, she needs 80 square feet - 18 square feet = 62 square feet of additional carpet to cover the whole floor. \n\nTherefore, Jesse needs 62 square feet more carpet to cover the whole floor.'

'First, we know that the grasshopper jumped 21 inches. We also know that the grasshopper jumped 25 inches farther than the frog, so the frog must have jumped 21 + 25 = 46 inches. Lastly, we know that the mouse jumped 16 inches less than the frog, so the mouse must have jumped 46 - 16 = 30 inches. \n\nTherefore, the grasshopper jumped 21 - 30 = 9 inches farther than the mouse. The answer is 9 inches.'
'A: The grasshopper jumped 21 inches, the frog jumped 21 + 25 = 46 inches, and the mouse jumped 46 - 16 = 30 inches. Therefore, the grasshopper jumped 21 - 30 = 9 inches farther than the mouse. The answer is 9 inches.'

'To find out how many visitors came to the Buckingham palace in the past 89 days, we need to add up the visitors from each day.\n\n512 visitors came on the current day\n471 visitors came the previous day\n808 visitors came the day before that\n\nAdding all the visitors together:\n512 + 471 + 808 = 1791 visitors\n\nTherefore, a total of 1791 visitors visited the Buckingham palace within the past 89 days.'

'To find out how many visitors visited the Buckingham palace within the past 89 days, we need to add up the number of visitors on each day. \n\n512 visitors on the current day\n471 visitors on the previous day\n808 visitors on the day before that\n\nAdding these numbers together: 512 + 471 + 808 = 1791 visitors in total over the past 3 days. \n\nIf we assume the same number of visitors each day for the past 89 days, we can multiply 1791 by 89 to find the total number of visitors over the past 89 days. \n\n1791 * 89 = 159,399 visitors in total over the past 89 days. \n\nTherefore, 159,399 visitors visited the Buckingham palace within the past 89 days.'

To find out how many more sacks of ripe oranges are harvested than unripe oranges, we subtract the number of sacks of unripe oranges from the number of sacks of ripe oranges: 44 - 25 = 19. Therefore, 19 more sacks of ripe oranges are harvested per day compared to unripe oranges. The answer is 19.'

'Let x be the number of books Paul sold in the garage sale. Initially, Paul had 2 books, then he sold x books, and bought 150 new ones, resulting in a total of 2 - x + 150 = 58 books. \n\nSolving this equation, we get:\n2 - x + 150 = 58\n148 - x = 58\n-x = -90\nx = 90\n\nTherefore, Paul sold 90 books in the garage sale.'
'First, we know that Paul had 2 books. Then, he sold some in a garage sale and bought 150 new ones. So, after selling some books, he had 2 - x (number of books sold) + 150 = 58 books. \nSolving for x, we get:\n2 - x + 150 = 58\n148 - x = 58\n-x = -90\nx = 90\nTherefore, Paul sold 90 books in the garage sale.'
'First, Paul had 2 books. After selling some in a garage sale, he bought 150 new ones, bringing the total to 58 books. This means he sold 2 + 150 - 58 = 94 books. Paul sold 94 books in the garage sale.'
'First, we know that Paul had 2 books. After selling some in a garage sale, he bought 150 new ones. So, he had 2 - x (number of books sold) + 150 = 58 books. \n\nThis can be simplified to 152 - x = 58. \n\nSolving for x, x = 152 - 58 = 94. Therefore, Paul sold 94 books in the garage sale.'
'First, we know that Paul had 2 books and then bought 150 new ones, so he had 2 + 150 = 152 books. If he now has 58 books, that means he sold 152 - 58 = 94 books. Paul sold 94 books in the garage sale.'
'To find out how many books Paul sold, we first need to subtract the number of books he currently has from the total number of books he bought after selling some.\n\nTotal books bought after selling some = 2 (initial books) + 150 (new books) = 152\n\nBooks sold = Total books bought after selling some - Current number of books = 152 - 58 = 94\n\nPaul sold 94 books in the garage sale.'

'First, we need to calculate how many crayons Paul had left at the end of the school year. He started with 531 crayons and had 391 left, so he used 531 - 391 = 140 crayons.\n\nSince Paul did not lose any erasers, he still has all 38 erasers. Now we need to find out how many more crayons he had left than erasers. He had 140 more crayons than erasers. The answer is 140.'
'To find out how many more crayons than erasers Paul had left, we first need to calculate the number of erasers he had left. He started with 531 crayons and 38 erasers, so he had a total of 531 + 38 = 569 items in the beginning. At the end of the school year, he had 391 items left. \n\nTo find out how many erasers he had left, we subtract the number of crayons he had left from the total number of items he started with:\n569 - 391 = 178 erasers left\n\nNow, to find out how many more crayons than erasers he had left, we subtract the number of erasers left from the total number of items he had left:\n391 - 178 = 213 more crayons than erasers\n\nTherefore, Paul had 213 more crayons than erasers left at the end of the school year.'

'A: Dave had 10 apps on his phone. He added 11 new apps, making a total of 21 apps. After deleting some, he had 4 apps left. To find out how many apps he deleted, we subtract the number of apps he had left (4) from the total number of apps (21), which gives us 17 apps deleted. So, Dave deleted 17 apps.'
'First, Dave had 10 apps on his phone. He added 11 new apps, making the total number of apps on his phone 10 + 11 = 21. After deleting some apps, he had 4 left. So, he deleted 21 - 4 = 17 apps. Dave deleted 17 apps in total.'

'First, we know that there were originally 5 roses and 3 orchids in the vase. After Jessica cut some more flowers, there are now 12 roses and 2 orchids in the vase. \n\nSo, Jessica added 12-5 = 7 more roses to the vase. \nAnd she added 2-3 = -1 (or 1 less) orchids to the vase. \n\nTherefore, there are 7 more roses than orchids in the vase now. The answer is 7.'
'First, we know there were 5 roses and 3 orchids in the vase originally. After Jessica cut some more flowers, there are now 12 roses and 2 orchids in the vase. This means she added 7 roses (12-5) and subtracted 1 orchid (3-2). Therefore, there are now 7 more roses than orchids in the vase. The answer is 7.'
"To find out how many more roses than orchids are in the vase now, we first need to calculate how many roses and orchids Jessica added to the vase.\n\nOriginally, there were 5 roses and 3 orchids in the vase. After Jessica added more flowers, there are now 12 roses and 2 orchids in the vase. This means Jessica added 12-5 = 7 roses and 2-3 = -1 orchids.\n\nSince you can't have a negative number of orchids, we need to adjust the calculation. Jessica actually added 7 roses and 1 orchid.\n\nNow, to find out how many more roses than orchids are in the vase now, we subtract the number of orchids from the number of roses: 7-1 = 6. There are 6 more roses than orchids in the vase now. The answer is 6."

The answer is 7.'

"To find out how many more roses than orchids are in the vase now, we first need to calculate how many roses and orchids Jessica cut from her flower garden.\n\nInitially, there were 5 roses and 3 orchids in the vase. Now, there are 12 roses and 2 orchids in the vase. This means Jessica cut 12-5 = 7 roses and 2-3 = -1 orchids from her flower garden.\n\nSince we can't have negative orchids, let's assume she didn't cut any orchids. Therefore, she cut 7 roses from her flower garden.\n\nNow, we compare the number of roses and orchids in the vase. There are 12 roses and 2 orchids, so there are 12-2 = 10 more roses than orchids in the vase now. The answer is 10."

The answer is 7.'

'A: Jessica cut 16 more roses from her garden and put them in the vase. After adding these roses, there are now 23 roses in the vase. So, if we subtract the 16 roses she cut from the total, we can find out how many roses were originally in the vase. 23 - 16 = 7. Therefore, there were 7 roses in the vase at the beginning. The answer is 7.'
"Let's denote the initial number of roses in the vase as x. Jessica cut 16 more roses and put them in the vase, so the total number of roses in the vase now is x + 16. We are given that there are now 23 roses in the vase, so we can set up the equation x + 16 = 23. \n\nBy solving this equation, we find that x = 7. Therefore, there were 7 roses in the vase at the beginning."

'Since 252 pickers fill 108 drums of grapes per day, in one day they fill 252*108 = 27,216 drums of grapes. \n\nTherefore, in 58 days, they would fill 58*27,216 = 1,577,088 drums of grapes. The answer is 1,577,088 drums of grapes.'
'First, we need to find out how many drums of grapes are filled per day by the pickers. If 252 pickers fill 108 drums of grapes per day, then each picker fills 108/252 = 0.4286 drums of grapes per day.\n\nNext, we need to calculate how many drums of grapes would be filled in 58 days. Since each picker fills 0.4286 drums per day, in 58 days they would fill 58 x 0.4286 = 24.857 drums of grapes.\n\nTherefore, in 58 days, 24.857 drums of grapes would be filled by the pickers.'

'First, we know that each basket has 4 red peaches. So, together the red peaches in both baskets total 4 + 4 = 8 peaches. Since there are a total of 12 peaches in both baskets, that means there are 12 - 8 = 4 green peaches in both baskets. Since each basket has some more green peaches, that means there are 4 green peaches divided by 2 baskets, so each basket has 2 green peaches. The answer is 2.'
'To find out how many green peaches are in each basket, we first need to determine the total number of red peaches in both baskets. Since each basket has 4 red peaches, and there are 2 baskets, there are a total of 4 red peaches x 2 baskets = 8 red peaches.\n\nNext, we need to find out how many green peaches are in each basket. If there are a total of 12 peaches in all baskets, and we already know there are 8 red peaches, then there must be 12 total peaches - 8 red peaches = 4 green peaches.\n\nTherefore, each basket has 4 green peaches. The answer is 4.'
'First, we know that each basket has 4 red peaches. So, there are a total of 2 * 4 = 8 red peaches in both baskets.\nSince there are a total of 12 peaches in both baskets, we can subtract the number of red peaches to find out how many green peaches are in both baskets. \n12 total peaches - 8 red peaches = 4 green peaches.\nSo, there are 4 green peaches in both baskets. Since each basket has the same number of green peaches, there are 4/2 = 2 green peaches in each basket. The answer is 2.'
'A: Each basket has 4 red peaches and a total of 12 peaches in both baskets. That means there are 12 - (2 x 4) = 4 green peaches in total. Since there are 2 baskets, each basket has 4 green peaches. The answer is 4.'

Since each basket has some green peaches, that means there are 4 green peaches divided between the 2 baskets, so each basket has 4 / 2 = 2 green peaches. Therefore, each basket has 2 green peaches."

'A: The mailman has to give 38 pieces of junk mail to each of the 78 blocks. If there are 19 houses on a block, then the total number of houses is 78 * 19 = 1482 houses. To distribute 38 pieces of junk mail to each house, the mailman should give each house 38 / 1482 = 0.0256, which is approximately 0.03 pieces of junk mail. Therefore, the mailman should give each house approximately 0.03 pieces of junk mail.'
'A: The mailman has to give 38 pieces of junk mail to each of the 78 blocks. If there are 19 houses on a block, then the total number of houses in all blocks would be 78 * 19 = 1482 houses. To find out how many pieces of junk mail each house should receive, we divide the total number of junk mail pieces by the total number of houses: 38 * 78 / 1482 = 2. The mailman should give each house 2 pieces of junk mail.'

"To find the width of Jesse's room, we can use the formula for the area of a rectangle, which is length x width = area. \n\nGiven that the area of the room is 10 square feet and the length is 5 feet, we can plug these values into the formula:\n\n5 feet x width = 10 square feet\n\nTo solve for the width, we divide both sides by 5 feet:\n\nwidth = 10 square feet / 5 feet\nwidth = 2 feet\n\nTherefore, the width of Jesse's room is 2 feet."
"To find the width of Jesse's room, we can use the formula for the area of a rectangle, which is length x width = area.\n\nSince the area of Jesse's room is 10 square feet and the length is 5 feet, we can plug in the values:\n\n5 feet x width = 10 square feet\n\nTo solve for the width, we divide both sides by 5:\n\nwidth = 10 square feet / 5 feet\nwidth = 2 feet\n\nTherefore, the width of Jesse's room is 2 feet."
"A: To find the width of Jesse's room, we can use the formula for the area of a rectangle, which is length x width = area. Since the area of the room is 10 square feet and the length is 5 feet, we can plug these values into the formula and solve for the width. \n\n5 feet x width = 10 square feet\nwidth = 10 square feet / 5 feet\nwidth = 2 feet\n\nTherefore, the width of Jesse's room is 2 feet."
"To find the width of Jesse's room, you can divide the total square footage of the room by the length of the room. Since the total square footage required for the carpet is 10 square feet and the length of the room is 5 feet, you can calculate the width by dividing 10 by 5. \n\n10 square feet / 5 feet = 2 feet \n\nTherefore, the width of Jesse's room is 2 feet."
"A: To find the width of Jesse's room, we need to divide the total square footage of the room by the length of the room. Since the room is 10 square feet and 5 feet long, the width of the room would be 10 divided by 5, which is 2 feet. Therefore, the width of Jesse's room is 2 feet."
"To find the width of Jesse's room, we need to divide the total square footage of the room by the length of the room. Since the room is 10 square feet and 5 feet long, the width of her room would be 10 square feet / 5 feet = 2 feet. Therefore, the width of Jesse's room is 2 feet."
"To find the width of Jesse's room, we can use the formula for the area of a rectangle: Area = Length x Width. \n\nGiven that the area of the room is 10 square feet and the length is 5 feet, we can plug in the values and solve for the width:\n\n10 = 5 x Width\nWidth = 10 / 5\nWidth = 2\n\nTherefore, the width of Jesse's room is 2 feet."

Therefore, the mailman should give a total of 4 pieces of junk mail to each of the 272 houses, which is 4 * 272 = 1088 pieces of junk mail in total. The answer is 1088.'

'To find out how many books Frank read, we first need to calculate how many pages he reads in a day. Since it takes him 12 days to finish one book with 66 pages, he reads 66/12 = 5.5 pages per day. \n\nIf he takes 492 days to finish all the books, we divide 492 by the number of days it takes to finish one book (12 days) to find out how many books he read in total. \n\n492 days / 12 days per book = 41 books\n\nTherefore, Frank read a total of 41 books.'
'To find out how many books Frank read, we first need to calculate how many pages he reads in a day. Since each book has 66 pages and it takes him 12 days to finish a book, Frank reads 66 / 12 = 5.5 pages per day.\n\nIf he takes 492 days to finish all the books, we can divide 492 by the number of days it takes him to finish one book (12 days) to find out how many books he read. \n\n492 / 12 = 41\n\nTherefore, Frank read 41 books in total.'
'To find out how many books Frank read, we need to first calculate how many pages he reads in a day. Since each book has 66 pages and it takes him 12 days to finish a book, he reads 66 pages / 12 days = 5.5 pages per day.\n\nIf it took him 492 days to finish all the books, and he reads 5.5 pages per day, then he read a total of 492 days * 5.5 pages per day = 2706 pages.\n\nSince each book has 66 pages, the number of books he read is 2706 pages / 66 pages per book = 41 books.\n\nTherefore, Frank read 41 books.'
'First, we know that each book has 66 pages and Frank takes 12 days to finish each book. This means that Frank reads 66 pages in 12 days. To find out how many pages he reads in 492 days, we divide 492 by 12, which equals 41. This means that Frank read 41 books in total. The answer is 41 books.'
'First, we need to determine how many pages Frank reads in a day. Since each book has 66 pages and it takes him 12 days to finish a book, he reads 66/12 = 5.5 pages per day. \n\nNext, we need to determine how many pages he reads in total in 492 days. Since he reads 5.5 pages per day, in 492 days he would have read 492 * 5.5 = 2706 pages in total. \n\nSince each book has 66 pages, we can calculate how many books he read by dividing the total number of pages he read by the number of pages in each book. Therefore, he read 2706/66 = 41 books in total. \n\nSo, Frank read 41 books in total.'

"First, let's figure out how many push-ups David did. Since David did 36 more push-ups than Zachary, he did 58 + 36 = 94 push-ups.\n\nNext, let's figure out how many crunches David did. Since David did 33 less crunches than Zachary, he did 33 crunches.\n\nNow, let's compare the number of push-ups and crunches Zachary did. Zachary did 58 push-ups and 33 crunches. Therefore, Zachary did 58 - 33 = 25 more push-ups than crunches. The answer is 25."

Since David did 33 less crunches than Zachary, we can calculate that David did 33 crunches.\n\nNow, we need to find out how many more push-ups than crunches Zachary did. So, his earnings from working overtime during the harvest season would be 1091 weeks * $939/week = $1,024,149.\n\nTherefore, Lewis earns a total of $30,548 + $1,024,149 = $1,054,697 during the harvest season.'

'To find out how many alligators were not hiding, we first need to determine how many alligators were originally in the cage. There were 75 alligators in the cage and 19 were hiding, so 75 - 19 = 56 alligators were not hiding. Therefore, there were 56 alligators that were not hiding.'
'First, we need to find out how many snakes and alligators were originally in the cage. There were 3 snakes and 75 alligators, totaling 78 animals. \n\nNext, we need to find out how many animals are currently in the cage after some of them are hiding. There are 82 snakes and 19 alligators hiding, totaling 101 animals. \n\nTo find out how many alligators are not hiding, we subtract the total number of animals currently in the cage from the original total. \n\n78 (original total) - 101 (current total) = 23 alligators. \n\nTherefore, there are 23 alligators that are not hiding.'
'First, we need to determine the total number of snakes and alligators that were originally in the cage. There were 3 snakes and 75 alligators, totaling 3 + 75 = 78 animals in the cage.\n\nNext, we need to calculate the total number of animals that were hiding. There were 82 snakes and 19 alligators hiding, totaling 82 + 19 = 101 animals hiding.\n\nTo find out how many alligators were not hiding, we subtract the number of animals hiding from the original total in the cage. So, 78 - 101 = 23 alligators were not hiding. The answer is 23.'
'First, we know that there were originally 3 snakes and 75 alligators in the cage. Then, 82 snakes and 19 alligators were hiding. So, the number of alligators not hiding would be 75 - 19 = 56 alligators. The answer is 56.'
'To find out how many alligators were not hiding, we first need to determine the original number of alligators in the cage. There were 75 alligators in the cage originally. If 19 alligators were hiding, that means 75 - 19 = 56 alligators were not hiding. Therefore, there were 56 alligators that were not hiding. The answer is 56.'

'First, we know that there were originally 3 snakes and 75 alligators in the cage. Then, 82 snakes and 19 alligators were hiding. This means that there are now 3+82=85 snakes and 75+19=94 alligators in total. Since there were originally 75 alligators and now there are 94 alligators in total, there are 94-75=19 alligators that were not hiding. The answer is 19.'
'First, we need to find out how many snakes and alligators were originally in the cage. There were 3 snakes and 75 alligators, totaling 78 animals in the cage. \n\nNext, we need to find out how many animals are currently in the cage. If 82 snakes and 19 alligators were hiding, that means there are 82 - 3 = 79 snakes and 75 - 19 = 56 alligators currently in the cage. \n\nTherefore, the number of alligators that are not hiding is 56. The answer is 56.'
'First, we know that there were originally 3 snakes and 75 alligators in the cage. Then, 82 snakes and 19 alligators were hiding. This means that there are now 3+82=85 snakes and 75+19=94 alligators in total. Since the total number of alligators in the cage is 94, and we know that there were originally 75 alligators, we can calculate that 94-75=19 alligators were not hiding. Therefore, there are 19 alligators that are not hiding.'
'First, we know that Paige and her mom planted 55 seeds in total. They put 15 seeds in each flower bed. So, they planted 55/15 = 3.67 flower beds. Since they cannot plant a fraction of a flower bed, we can say they planted 3 flower beds in total. Then, we know that only 60 seeds grew into flowers in each flower bed. So, they grew 60 * 3 = 180 flowers in total. The answer is 180 flowers.'
"First, we need to determine how many flower beds they planted. Since they put 15 seeds in each flower bed and planted a total of 55 seeds, they planted 55/15 = 3.67 flower beds. Since you can't have a fraction of a flower bed, we can assume they planted 3 flower beds.\n\nIf only 60 seeds grew into flowers in each flower bed, then they grew a total of 60 * 3 = 180 flowers. Therefore, Paige and her mom grew 180 flowers in total."
"First, we know that Paige and her mom planted 55 seeds in total. They put 15 seeds in each flower bed. So, to find out how many flower beds they planted, we divide the total number of seeds by the number of seeds in each flower bed: 55 / 15 = 3.66. Since we can't have a fraction of a flower bed, we know they planted 3 flower beds. And since only 60 seeds grew into flowers in each flower bed, we multiply 3 (number of flower beds) by 60 (number of seeds that grew into flowers in each flower bed): 3 * 60 = 180. Therefore, Paige and her mom grew 180 flowers in total."
"First, we know that Paige and her mom planted a total of 55 seeds. They put 15 seeds in each flower bed. So, they must have planted 55 / 15 = 3.67 flower beds. Since we can't have a fraction of a flower bed, we can round down to 3 flower beds. Finally, if 60 seeds grew into flowers in each flower bed, then they grew a total of 3 flower beds * 60 flowers per bed = 180 flowers in total. So, Paige and her mom grew 180 flowers."

'First, we know they planted a total of 55 seeds. They put 15 seeds in each flower bed. So, to find out how many flower beds they planted, we divide 55 by 15, which equals 3 flower beds. \n\nNext, we know that only 60 seeds grew into flowers in each flower bed. Since they planted 3 flower beds, we multiply 60 by 3 to find out how many flowers they grew in total. \n\n60 (seeds) x 3 (flower beds) = 180 flowers\n\nTherefore, Paige and her mom grew 180 flowers in total.'
"To find out how many flowers they grew, we first need to determine how many flower beds they planted. Since they put 15 seeds in each flower bed and planted a total of 55 seeds, they must have planted 55/15 = 3.67 flower beds. Since they can't plant a fraction of a flower bed, we round down to 3 flower beds. \n\nIf only 60 seeds grew into flowers in each flower bed, then they grew a total of 3 flower beds * 60 flowers per bed = 180 flowers in total. Therefore, Paige and her mom grew 180 flowers."
